21st Century House in Vienna
Pavilion in a new place
Ingeborg Winsowski
Architectural history with ups, downs and happy endings. The Austrian pavilion for the 1958 World Exhibition in Brussels won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, empty and was abandoned.
Now it is being re-opened as an exhibition center.
The Austrian Pavilion, designed by Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 World’s Fair in Brussels, is a famous example of modern post-war architecture with its simple forms, glass halls that boldly expressed a belief in technological progress.
The Schwanzer Pavilion won the Architecture Grand Prix in 1958 for its lightweight soaring steel and glass structure.
The building is considered a milestone in modern architecture.
This made the architect so famous that he also built the Austrian Pavilion at the next World's Fair.
He eventually became world famous in 1973 with his legendary BMW four-cylinder tower and her sister, the bowl-shaped building.
The pavilion, conceived as a temporary exhibition building, was moved to the Swiss Garden near Vienna's South Station, converted and opened as the 20th Century Museum in 1962 - and is often referred to as the "20th Century House" for this reason.
However, the building was not suitable for the museum for technical and spatial reasons - there were no walls on which to hang works of art, and poor air conditioning.
However, it continued to be used until modern art in Vienna got a new home.
The house had been empty since 2001, and his condition was getting worse and worse.
Architect Adolf Krishanitz has now renovated the pavilion, which has been dubbed the “21st Century House” and will be used as a museum of contemporary art.
This museum is a branch of the Belvedere Museum, which will open the first exhibition on Tuesday evening - in all senses a joyful event.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Belvedere Gallery in 2007, contributed to the new venture.
Husslein-Arco, a graduate of the Faculty of Art History with a brilliant career as a figure skater in her youth who worked at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and eventually became the founder and director of the Museum of Modernity in Salzburg, convinced politicians and curators to continue the reconstruction, attracted public funds and private donations and made a decision on how the building would be used.
The new museum was to accommodate a permanent exhibition of the Fritz Votruba Foundation, a cafe and a bookstore along with modern art. An office building was also to be built.
Strict control & limited budget
Krishanitz was then the ideal candidate for the project.
He was known, of course, for the restoration and expansion of the Vienna Secession by Josef Olbrich, and won the competition, but he also studied with Schwanzer at the Vienna University of Technology, and the pavilion was for him "an exceptionally important place" where he attended exhibitions "almost every week".
He knew the original design and knew the tasks that stood in front of the building, a building that had already lost some of its grandeur and ease when it was moved to Vienna and transformed.
The problems that arose during the last restructuring were much more serious. The building was a "energy absorber," Krishanitz says.
The window profiles on the glass facade were replaced, fiberglass-enhanced safety glass was inserted, and the glass roof was replaced with high-strength safety glass.
The steel crossbars of the heat bridge were reinforced or replaced, and asbestos was removed from the ceilings.
Two lower floors have created space for new use of the building, a fallen light well between the building and the street provides lighting - a virtually new building, but still an elegant Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors were preserved, and the building was painted in the old red-brown color of corrosion protection.
The cinema hall is the same as it used to be.
All this under strict control of the museum management and with a limited budget.
“We often had to find material that was good, cheap and would have been approved by the museum management,” Krishanitz says, pointing to the uneven flooring in the basement.
The building remained flexible and light despite limitations, challenges and transformations.
Krishanitz noted recently that the pavilion "from Brussels" was rough - a typical history of "drops in the city".
Such an architecture is “always out of place” and yet it wants to “stimulate real awareness.”
The house of the 21st century is in a very right place, because when planning the city, unexpected luck happened. A completely redesigned "quarter of the main station" with offices and residential real estate grows around the Swiss Garden.
A second happy event may occur. The 21st-century house can be complemented by a second Krishanitz building - collector Francesca von Habsburg has acquired Berlin's Temporary Exhibition Hall and is reportedly negotiating with the city for its location next door in the Swiss Garden.
