Smart crows fill cities
Roaches are considered problem birds in many places. Experts today say that these very smart birds will not be able to be expelled from cities.
Some love birds, others would like to get rid of them as quickly as possible. Crows have been part of the urban landscape for centuries, but residents complaining about dirt and noise are becoming more and more in many settlements.
The solution to the problem of birds, however, has not yet been achieved.
At the first symposia on crows in the city of Lehr in East Frisia, experts argued that rooks can no longer be expelled from cities.
Experts from all over Germany discussed possible solutions.
Finding Alternatives in Cities
Conservatives argued that the root of the problem in cities was in the migration of specially protected rooks, pointing out that the use of chemicals in agriculture was increasingly destroying traditional habitats.
Hunting, expanding construction and cutting down traditional nesting trees made life difficult for birds.
The crows are protected.
In the town of Zest in Westphalia and in the northwest in Yever, Deepholtz, Achim near Bremen and Lera, there are large colonies with more than 600 parent pairs.
The controversial project of shooting crows in Lera caused disapproving newspaper headlines in 2005.
Critics have described trapping birds and hammering them with sticks as a particular cruelty.
“Ordinary displacement and scaring don’t work,” said architect and landscape designer Werner Clever of Lehr.
Hitting nests with a jet of water or cutting down trees often has undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser of Lara, Baden-Wurttemberg.
"Animals disperse, and large colonies divide and spread to other areas."
Intimidation is possible only as an exception next to hospitals, nursing homes and schools.
"We'll have to live with them. Getting rid of them is not an option."
In isolation from the surrounding areas, the problem in the cities will not be solved, - says the mayor of Lera Wolfgang Koelner.
A combination of deterring birds from needing protection in residential areas and encouraging them to return to other areas could be a solution.
"Information stands instead of chainsaws" was a slogan proposed by psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jurgens, who advocates a completely different approach to birds. "We need to be confident in ourselves to live with this problem."
Jurgens was one of the founders of the educational rave route in Asherberg in Schleswig-Holstein, where information about the life of very clever rooks is given on information stands.
The project is already of interest to tourists.
Jurgens also expressed her opinion on complaints about noise produced by birds. "Noise conveys a lot of information. They have a lot to say to each other."
The intelligence and ingenuity of these birds have become legends. Rookies often not only use tools to get hold of the piece, but also make the tools themselves.
Researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested the measure of bird intelligence on four rakes.
In one experiment, the birds quickly realized that it was necessary to knock on the board to get the moth larva.
Without much training, they learned the size and shape of the stone needed to knock down the plaque.
In another experiment, clever rooks had to solve a more complex problem.
The researchers placed a small bucket of moth larvae in a vertical cylinder.
The birds couldn't get their beaks.
But the researchers gave them pieces of wire.
All four birds used the wire to make hooks and used hooks to hook the bucket by the handle and pull it out of the cylinder.
Three of the four rooks coped with this on their first attempt.
