Mass Murders - The Human Dimension
Peter Englund’s intense and very kind new book, Beauty and Grief: A Personal History of the First World War, begins with a long list of characters from which the heart freezes.
Here’s a tip on how to read on: Carefully cut out this page and use it as a bookmark.
You will get to know these people very closely as Mr. Englund narrates, and this list of actors will be your GPS, your beacon in those moments when, like one of these men and women, you will get lost in the fog of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he wrote now is unusual, he describes it quite accurately as "an anti-history work."
It has few known names, important treaties or famous battles; there are almost no ambassadors, dexterous journalists or discussions of tactics and military equipment.
It's not so much a book about what it was, he explains, as "a book about what it was like." It's about "feelings, impressions, experiences, and state of mind."
The book "Beauty and Sorrow" weaved together the experience of 20 more or less unremarkable men and women on both sides of the front line, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and employees.
Some of these people will be heroes.
Someone will be captured, lose an arm or leg, go crazy or die.
Their lives shimmer here like church candles: new ones are added to many others, and some are extinguished at this time.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard of historical books.
This is an amendment to the idea that World War I was only a heavy trench war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully gives a panorama of other theaters of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
A bee hive falls on the soldiers in this book; one of them meets Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the unsolved problem is tsetse flies.
It's an exciting book, almost from the beginning.
War covers the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of smokeless gunpowder.
When the cannonade is not far away, and you are a woman and are at home with children, will you stay or run away?
Anyway, who's coming?
Almost no one understands what is happening and in general why it is necessary to fight in this war.
“The lack of facts,” notes Mr. Englund, “is filled with conjectures, assumptions, hopes, fears, obsessions, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors.”
Beauty and Sorrow traces the fate of such people as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor of the German High Seas Fleet.
Their stories are taken mainly from memoirs, letters and other already published materials.
Stories about their lives can be scary or exciting, but they are extremely alive thanks to the small moments and fragmentary details collected by Mr. Englund.
Many of them are about hardship and how to deal with it.
Telling the story of a German schoolgirl, he says: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz."
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, fake rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons".
He continues to talk about ersatz food in Germany.
It describes "meat made from pressed rice cooked in lamb fat (and decorated with fake bone made of wood); tobacco made from dried roots and dried potato peel; shoes battered with wood."
He notes that there were “837 registered meat substitutes allowed in sausage production, 511 registered coffee substitutes.”
Some stories speak of honor and courage.
One American notices in himself a craving for cruelty and says about the war: "You feel that, in the end, this is what men were created for, and not to sit in comfortable chairs with a cigarette and whiskey, an evening newspaper or a bestseller and claim that this show is civilization and under your starched shirt with cufflinks is not a barbarian."
The British soldier, on the contrary, notices that he is likely to die and no one will notice or grieve.
“When a person comes to terms with the idea of self-sacrifice, he would like to think that this will happen in front of the public,” he writes.
But on the contrary, it is frighteningly similar to a “sentenced person who is hanged secretly.”
Other comments concern old Europe, which is falling apart, and new kinds of fear.
“Conflict has increasingly become an economic competition,” writes Mr. Englund, “a war of factories.”
He notes the arrival of what he calls "a new species in the bestiary of the beginning of the century: a beautifully expressed and ideologically convinced mass murderer in a well-stitched suit who arranges a massacre sitting at a desk."
