Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Study You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was a regular guy outlining his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to a mass murder in Norway in July that killed 77 people, appeared at his first public court hearing.
Although Breivik could act alone, he was far from alone online: he spent a lot of time preparing to attack at his computer, communicating with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, the researchers wanted to learn more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - you just need to go to Facebook.
“We realized that it was not difficult to get close to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European cyber populism by the British research center DEMOS.
Facebook’s stock of personal data is so large, Bartlett says, that researchers could easily use the site’s advertising tool to highlight the demographics they need with scientific accuracy — something marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing fans across Europe and then pitched them ads, but instead of showing a new group or diet product, the ads offered the user a survey that asked questions about their level of education, attitudes to violence, and optimism about their own future.
With the help of Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 members of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - even without leaving the office.
“It’s a whole new way of doing research,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results aren’t as startling: Online supporters of right-wing groups are more likely young males dissatisfied with immigration.
“Those who combine their online activity with offline activity are smarter, more democratic, and less aggressive than those who just hide behind a monitor.”
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to explore everything from health issues to social trends, which are expressed in “Likes”, posts on the wall and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three posts a day, Facebook’s “super-relevant information” is causing a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the site name in the headline by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it provides an opportunity to study people who cannot be approached on the street with a notebook.
“In the past, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them.”
“You’d have to join the party and they’d never accept you,” Bartlett says.
"Facebook eliminates all of this - you reach out to them directly."
Others say that with this site it would be possible to identify and research social health issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their drunken exploits on Facebook were significantly more at risk of alcoholism than students who were silent about it.
Moreno suggests that students' peers, such as their dorm mentors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who updates drunk statuses too often.
“You can’t solve a problem without identifying it,” said Washington Post co-author Dimitri Christakis and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute.
"We found a way to identify children at risk who would not otherwise be found."
Facebook also constantly extracts various kinds of data about its users.
The site's data processing team processed statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, mid-term voter turnout in 2010, and the National Happiness Index (mostly using information that only they have access to - cyberfreedom champions have long insisted that the site should make its vast collection of data publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what about when Facebook users become participants in a study they don’t even know about?
While researchers have well-defined standards for conducting offline research, online data is publicly available.
“I don’t think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher can observe their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a study he conducted in 2006 using students’ public Facebook pages.
"As far as they could imagine, it was just between them and their friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline there is no guarantee that the object of the study is extremely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much information in the profile and on the user page is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two very different things,” Selwyn says.
That’s why, despite years of his work in technology research, Selwyn thinks notebook and pen are still the best research tools one can use.
“Nothing can replace going into the real world and communicating with real people,” he says.
“Social research is supposed to be about social research, and much of social research is still happening offline.”
