Lying ruins careers and shakes countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by denying his antics, which was quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards was charged with financial fraud during the campaign related to the concealment of extramarital affairs.
And again, no one living at the time would ever forget the media circus with President Bill Clinton caught lying about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in office.
Stories of cheating in school and college exams are common.
There were cases when teachers gave students answers to the tests in order to have a good assessment of the results of their activities.
Mentors who have to teach the opposite send a message that lies and fraud are acceptable.
How many lies are we facing?
During one day, as studies show, you can lie 10 to 200 times.
Now it is assumed that a significant part of this is a lie for salvation.
Another study found that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting each other.
Identifying lies or incriminating lies is a necessary skill for everyone, both for personal and professional purposes.
Unlike a room game similar to, say, a charade where you have to exclaim "Found!", lie detection is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities engaged in comprehensive research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One result of the study is that most of the old myths about lying have been debunked.
The liars look in the eyes.
They do not always stutter, stutter, blush or fuss.
It is not necessary to conclude from this that liars are difficult to notice and difficult to expose.
An experienced liar can get to the truth by observing the structure of statements, facial expressions, the structure of questions, and temporal characteristics.
I’ve spent several years researching scientific discoveries in a vast and ever-growing segment of the knowledge about lies, and it’s clear that detecting lies is a modern skill that’s easy to learn and helps navigate in our complex world — especially if your professional responsibilities include recruiting, interviewing, negotiating, or managing.
Good liars are great at reading others, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men lie more about themselves, while women lie more about others, usually to protect someone’s feelings that married people lie less to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they say are most often brazen).
We also know that if you are perceived as a cheater, others will feel less guilty about cheating on you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your object.
This is called "initial state determination".
This helps provide a starting point for assessing changes further.
Observe the posture, laughter, voice characteristics of your object.
It would be good for you to know if a person is constantly tapping his feet in normal condition, then you will not make unfair accusations when you see a kicking in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for groups of deceptive verbal and non-verbal actions.
Treat these groups as red flags, not proof of deception.
Deceivers can fix the upper part of their body when they try to remember their history, they can put their feet towards the door, lean toward the exit, change their posture in a certain way or show "relief after an interview" - this exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture when all the difficult questions are behind.
Investigators often falsify the signal of the end of the interrogation, just to look at this relief after the interview.
So, pay attention to the speech of your object.
Scott Peterson is known to have stumbled and used the intervening time claiming his murdered wife was alive, leading to her search across the country.
Proprietary people may also use distancing in speech: "I didn't have a sexual relationship with this woman ... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat the difficult question completely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use "qualifying language" when answering a difficult question: "Okay... truth be told... as far as I know... as far as I know."
This makes the answer more emotional than factual, and is often a red flag.
There is no magic means to detect lies, but you can master the skill of detecting deception.
These skills will increase the chances of everyone not to become a victim of skilled crooks in professional and personal life.
