The decline in economic activity caused, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, during the first three quarters there was an accelerated increase in the unemployment rate, from January to March, 55.053 residents of Sinaloa were unemployed, with a share of 4.53% of the economically active population, in the second quarter the share increased to 5.28%, and from July to September it continued to grow to 6.19%, a share that is more than the number of people.
Reduced liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is fraught with many factors, for economist Gerardo Lopez Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the Autonomous University (UAS), the rise in unemployment can be explained indirectly, by actions that were taken in public policy.
“What we are seeing now is rising unemployment, which is associated with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market in order to limit the resources imposed by the law that was passed in Congress to combat money laundering, since it is not easy for people who illegally own dollars to work with them, invest and use them in something,” he said.
Stopped immigration
Lopez Cervantes said there is also a demographic factor in the rise in unemployment.
“The number of people who leave the state in search of work abroad in the United States was limited, primarily because of difficulties with entry, and secondly because once they entered, they already face many difficulties in finding work, so a group of people stay and demand jobs here in the state, as a result, the unemployment rate rises,” he said.
Violation of formal requirements
Sinaloa's labor market analysis is getting worse when you look at the large number of violations that prevail in working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the active population of the state works without being mentioned as workers in any social protection institution.
In addition to unemployment and malpractice, another reminder of working in the state is represented by low wages; the state has the lowest salaries in the country, according to records from the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Ministry of Labor and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was 5,352 pesos before September, well below the national average of 7,375 pesos.
Reduction of FDI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and high unemployment, 2011 saw the largest outflow of foreign direct investment in the last 10 years, according to the Ministry of Finance, from January to July, the state’s FDI totaled $630,697, which shows a drop of 87.74 percent compared to $5,143,312 during the same period last year.
For its part, the State Ministry of Economic Development recorded only 17,280,000 pesos of investment during the year, which mainly fell on service companies.
Debt
Amid the economic downturn, the state government requested in July during the state Congress approval of a loan of 3 billion pesos, which would be used to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 municipalities to revive the economy, only 2,600 million pesos were approved at the local level, and no sector of the state's economy was expected to benefit from the debt until November.
Reactions
For business representatives, the first year of the government of Mario Lopez Valdés demonstrates the lack of government capabilities.
Miguel Loredo Lopez, president of the National Chamber of Manufacturing, said that during 2011 there was a lack of agreement on the wishes of various sectors, including the state government itself.
“The efficiency of the economy in Sinaloa this year was really low, we have to work hard to regain the positions lost this year, in 2012 we must redouble our efforts, we have not been able to coordinate the efforts of everyone and, above all, the good and synchronized work of the new government team, we hope that next year will be much better,” he said.
Economic slowdown
Lopez Loredo said events such as early frosts this year halted the state's economy and its efficiency and growth were limited.
“Low volumes of the economy are the result of several events, including frost, one of the main effects was a slow economy that does not become fast enough to create economic dynamics that allow us to have an acceptable level of processes, goods and services and, therefore, at the end of the year we close it below our expectations,” he said.
Revision of direction
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said the state needs to continue the most dynamic production activity.
“Overall, we found that we were working on it, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that will redefine the direction and economic course of the state, it is necessary to mobilize all the material and human resources that Sinaloa has,” he said.
Work to be undertaken
President Coparmex stressed the importance of determining the future direction in order to better guide the government’s efforts.
“Overall, I would say that the government is trying to be successful in various areas, there is little progress in terms of economic development, but it is important to develop a long-term program,” he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in its own way of conducting public policy.
“There are facts that allow us to say that the government is starting to get involved in the work, and that I can say that some work has been done, and I think the government is aware that much more needs to be done,” he said.
