The court will approve the “transition to digital television” in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that have swept the world in recent years.
The Supreme Court has rejected constitutional claims made by the Senate and House of Representatives against a presidential decree that shifts the so-called “digital TV transition” from 2021 to 2015 because eight votes were not cast to annul it.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the court, Juan Silva Mesa, believed that President Felipe Calderon had not exceeded his authority by issuing a decree detailing actions to transition to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, the constitutional claims made by the Senate were rejected due to the lack of a qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to pronounce on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft statement, prepared by Minister Olga Sanchez Cordero, proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional because the regulation of the radio and television program is a right enshrined in law by the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the legislative reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sanchez Cordero voted for the project.
On this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to refute the decree and support the complaints, Minister Sanchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions mentioned in it regarding the transition to digital broadcasting.
At the ministerial meeting, it was also decided to reject the demand of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into a discussion of the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sanchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project in the sense that the federal executive power can not determine the general rules of the measures for which the state administration should be prepared.
"I also don't believe that if this happened, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and recalled that planning public policy in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, is relevant to the federal executive branch, which has a constitutional mandate, the management of the state.
Replacing analog signals with digital signals - one of the most important changes that have occurred in recent years - has led to better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would mean postponing the benefits of digital transformation, which involves meeting societal needs that have not only a technical dimension, “as it covers economic, social, political, and national security issues.”
These issues, he said, "require the work of the entire system, formed on the principle of state economic management, includes a group of authorities that the Constitution combines into the state executive power."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and did so with the help of the executive branch, despite the presence of highly specialized technical institutions.
From this it cannot be concluded that the government, by passing the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competence of Congress, ensures in the administrative sphere the observance of laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly, he said.
In Michoacan analyze the possibility of counting the “voice for voice”
The difference between the first and second places in the gubernatorial elections is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes accounted for by 879 out of a total of 6.074 protocols.
The possibility of a vote-by-vote count is real with respect to this year’s election process in Michoacan, where, according to data from the Preliminary Election Results Program (PRRA), the difference between first and second place in gubernatorial elections is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes accounted for 879 out of a total of 6,074 protocols.
In light of this, the Chairman of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacan (IVM), Maria de Los Angeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral corps approved a set of principles to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
As it should be recalled, Michoacan did not pass the State Constitution or the Electoral Code or the Voting Rights Act, as the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force in this electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel did not include its publication within the timeframe specified in the law in the State Official Gazette, stating that he had some objections.
On the same day, November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice (SCJ) ruled on a constitutional claim brought by the local legislature and called the state representative's vote on constitutional reform "invalid and illegal" because he has no right to "allow or support them."
In an interview about the possibility of a “vote-by-vote” Maria de los Angeles Llanderal argued that with the adoption of suitable principles by the General Council of the IVM, it will be possible to present a partial or complete counting of votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, a partial recount of one or more ballot boxes may be made under the conditions that: the results of the protocols do not coincide; there is no protocol for voting and counting documents in the ballot box or it is not at the chairman’s office; or when there are obvious errors or corrections in the protocol.
In addition, a general recount of votes in all ballot boxes may take place when there is a sign that the difference between the proposed winner of the election in question and the one who received the second place in the vote is less than or equal to one percent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a petition from a representative of the party and/or coalition that nominated the second of the above-mentioned candidates.
A total recount will also be made if, at the end of the normal recount, it is established that the difference between the winner and the second-placed candidate is less than or equal to one percent, provided that there is a petition from the political party whose second-placed candidate is excluded from the ballot boxes that were counted in the partial recount.
It is worth noting that in this situation there are elections in Morelia, where, according to the PPRV, the difference between the first and second places is only 0.16 percent, even excluding 129 votes from the total number in 923 protocols.
