A new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the Italian president to introduce a new government that will face a crisis that has put the country on the brink of economic disaster.
Italy's appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet Wednesday with the president of Italy to introduce a new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and hurt the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace said Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, on Wednesday to confirm he could form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed largely of technocrats, though it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monty said he would present the president with the results of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
“I want to reaffirm my full confidence in the ability of our country to get out of this difficult period,” the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monty did not say directly that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles had been overcome.
“The structure is now well defined,” he said.
Monti completed the process of forming the government in less than three days, which is much less than usual, as Italy struggled with a political and financial crisis that brought the size of their debt to a critical level.
The administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore confidence in Italy.
At the heart of the pressure on Monti to hasten, volatile markets have set Italy’s BTP bond yield at 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to save.
Emma Marchegaglia, the leader of the Italian Employers' Federation, told reporters after a meeting with Monti, "We said we would actively support this government."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this critical situation.
Monti's chances of success were largely based on the support of the LDP party Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday due to the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts should lead to a good outcome," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centrist-right party, told reporters.
The support of the LDP, Italy's largest party, matters because until now many of its members have opposed the government's technocrat majority that forms Monti.
Parliamentary support
Monty’s new government should have strong parliamentary support for reforms that would likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or suspension of these attempts can lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks has stepped up pressure, warning that Monti’s failure could be a disaster.
Monti began his consultations on Monday with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations.
He'll end his series of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who allowed an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would step down, Italy’s debt value has now reached a critical level amid uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will be successful.
Saving Italy with a public debt of 1.8 billion euros would be too much for the modern financial defenders of the eurozone.
Monty said his government would exist until the next election, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians would only give him time to carry out reforms before calling a new election.
Monty said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but mainstream parties insist it should be composed only of technical experts, a testament to their dissatisfaction with the financial situation affecting the process.
Political sources reported that mutual distrust and disagreement of parties complicates the attempt to include political figures.
