Quintet included the country in the tour in honor of the twentieth anniversary of his career
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said that the band is ready to give one of the best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
It’s been over 20 years of waiting, but the band says it’s also a dream come true for them to play in this country.
This was a statement by bassist and founder, Jeff Ament, who gave an exclusive interview to Viva from Brazil last week.
The band is in South America as part of a 20-year tour and will make its only stop in Central America on Sunday, the 20th.
On that day, they will perform at the National Stadium starting at 7:30 p.m., along with the Los Angeles-based team The X and local band Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which is available online in The Nation.
For your fans from Costa Rica, is it a dream come true that Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica? Do you know what your fans are experiencing?
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is only our second visit to South and Central America, and so far everything is going well.
I've only been to Costa Rica once - on vacation, it's a beautiful country, and I think we can stay there for a few days.
We are very happy to bring our music there.
I ask about it because there is some dedication to the band; fans live in suspense in the days before the concert.
What do you say to your most loyal fans?
Thank you for being with us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, thank you for waiting so long, and we regret that it took us so long to get here.
Some people, in anticipation of your concert, refer to it as the biggest show of the year.
Does this add a bit of tension to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve played in the last 21 years have been in the last two weeks.
We had some great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope it got us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play here.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle, as far as these two things are concerned, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you learn about Costa Rica and its surf waves?
We have a lot of surf friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves here are incredible.
My friends always go surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, as well as Mexico, these are great places to surf, that's how we learned about it, from people who love surfing.
Looking at the tour, you can say that you made a grand show with a lot of songs.
What are you planning to do in Costa Rica?
Since we have never played there before, we have no limits on what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible with a wide variety of songs; we will try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with a wide variety of repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
How does that work?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can play more than 120 songs, and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs that we haven’t played for a while, it keeps us in tune and surprises us because it reminds us of the reasons why we loved those songs and what we might have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting to us and so I think it makes it more interesting to people.
This tour marks 20 years of your career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe what you did?
Yeah, absolutely.
First of all, I think none of us could ever have imagined that we would be in a rock band and the fact that we’ve been doing this for over 20 years makes it look like a dream come true.
We are thrilled with our success and we are very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and make music.
We are happy to go to places in the world where we have always wanted to go.
Things are going very well for us.
What does it mean for you to be a significant part of the flowering of grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of great collectives.
We are good friends with the guys from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's great when a movement grows out of a group of friends, and it's unusual.
From time to time, one group appears from the same city, but it is much more strange when five or ten groups appear at the same time in the same city.
We are proud and honored to be a part of the band from Seattle.
I still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden during their tour, so we are happy to be friends with all of them and for us the honor of being part of the Seattle sound that came out.
It’s also very strange that a band like yours stays together and in the same line-up for so long.
Yes, four of us were together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than many bands exist.
First, I think we're lucky we're still alive, and second, we care about others.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to this, musical paths have also been opened that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other's music, and things couldn't have been better.
Your attitude to the word fame was not easy; but thanks to your success, you were able to do whatever you wanted.
How do you find balance?
As we grew up, it became easier to find a balance.
We take care not to be on tour too long because it’s easy to get into this game of big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are here for the music, it reminds you that you have to respect the music and what made it, not deciding to be famous and be a rock star, something that none of us really cares about.
How do you remember your other project, Manother Love Bone?
I think we write really good songs and in the beginning it was great.
We were a band for almost three years and did not release any albums until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
There were a lot of disappointments because it took so long, and the most important thing is that we are still close friends with Bruce (Ferweser) and Greg (Gilmore) who started with us in the band, and when I hear a song or see a photo, I think of the incredible person Andy was, and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and a lot of things.
He was a wonderful man and we miss him.
Las Robertas will be in charge of opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you are familiar with her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose her for the opening?
Yes, the producers sent us some video offers and it was the band we liked the most, so we can’t wait to see what Las Robertas has to offer live and it should be very exciting.
Why are you constantly changing the words in Yellow Ledbetter at concerts?
It's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he uses the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
There are so many.
Among the first to come to mind are Heather Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukovsky...
There are so many of them that I can talk all day about the bassists I love.
