In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that sparked a protest from Uruguay and a recall for consultations of its ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group created from the most highly developed and developing countries, and has essentially had a tax information exchange agreement with the South American country since January this year to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to speed up the conclusion of tax exchange agreements in order to leave this “grey list” of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, made up of countries that do not use international standards of tax cooperation.
As for the trade plan, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004, which has increased trade between the two countries.
