MSS announces obesity gene search program
Social protection leads research into obesity gene in children and young adults; it is supported by IPN experts
The Mexican Social Security Institute (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect the obesity gene in children and young adults, called the “Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescence” protocol, which will provide a count of signs associated with overweight.
In a statement, Miguel Cruz Lopez, head of the Division of Medical Research in Biochemistry of the Specialized Hospital of the National Medical Center of the XXI Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was assembled.
This team is assisted by specialists and graduate students of the National Institute of Health of the Nation (NIPH) and the Center for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
In the study, the population (prescribed or not) is invited to participate by going to the MSSI sports centers participating in the study, in the Valley of Mexico, where tests will be conducted with children every Saturday, from 8:00 am.
He stressed that the protocol began to be conducted at the sports center in Cuautemoc (in the west of Mexico state), and since October 8, events have been held at the sports center in Nesaualcoyotl (eastern Mexico state).
Once the goal of attracting 500 to 600 children is achieved, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Center (southern Mexico City) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (northern Mexico City).
He explained that the purpose of this study is to understand the components and importance of genetics in relation to the development of obesity and to establish a risk factor among children and young Mexicans to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On November 14, World Diabetes Day will be celebrated, and the main goal is to gather three thousand children and adolescents aged 6 to 14 years with the permission of parents and under their supervision to fill out individual nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and the history of familial hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturday, anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, height and waist circumference), blood pressure and glucose, fat, cholesterol and insulin levels, and genetic analysis (to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity) will be carried out.
Cruz Lopez said the study reflected health care professionals’ concerns about the alarming weight gain among children.
Medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006 indicate that in just 6 years, there was an increase: in the case of boys, 77 percent were obese, in the case of girls, 47 percent; in terms of excess weight, there was also a significant increase,” said the MSSI specialist.
He said that the validity of the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican was 65 percent American Indian, 30 percent European, and five percent African, a condition that affected genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that the main consequence of the genetics of obesity is the body’s inability to burn excess energy that we consume (calories), and it is stored as fat.
The researcher explained that the immediate benefit for the participants is a comprehensive assessment of children, which can reveal whether they have at least some degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds on the neck (acants) and forearms means the likelihood of metabolic disorders and even prediabetes.
The information is treated with all confidentiality, the doctors transmit it in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the measurements and lifestyle changes that must be taken to avoid the disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main causes of overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of the TV and using transport at short distances instead of walking.
This is also due to the high consumption of calories, that is, an increase in the consumption of sugary drinks and carbohydrates (tamale, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and genetic predisposition, analyzed in this program.
Asphalt UNAM will be able to avoid cracks
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, developed polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of the best quality, resistant to environmental influences and temperature.
If the signals sent by the road surface were given attention, then it would be necessary to repair about 200 thousand pits for each rainy season in the metropolitan area in the Valley of Mexico, says Rafael Herrera Nahera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry UNAM, and adds that if the process of construction and maintenance of asphalt road surface is correct, the number of pits can be reduced or even reduced to zero.
In his lecture The Technological View of the Pits, read as part of the International Year of Chemistry, it is reported that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture with characteristics close to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen can be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and therefore counteract pit formation.
He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight called maltenes, which together give the road surface its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of bitumen is due to the fact that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it retains an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes brittle, he said.
This means that the resistance of street asphalt is not constant, but varies throughout the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, said a specialist in chemical engineering.
The scientist noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with a flexible coating, which consists of six layers of material, of which the last three include bitumen.
Among the uppermost layers is a bitumen composed of small stones lowered into the bitumen and then pressed.
Every stone that makes up this coating, he said, is immersed in bitumen.
When driving vehicles and applying effort, it helps forces to be very well distributed over the road surface.
If it was a modified asphalt, they would be distributed even better, said a chemical engineer.
On the asphalt surface, he added, is placed the last layer, which is called the wear layer, which is made of fine stone, in fact sand is also immersed in asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will come into contact with the wheels of transport, it should have more resistance than asphalt and provide road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and distribute this effort, the wear layer also requires proper thickness, and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the condition of asphalt.
When the earth is wet, the water penetrates the coating and it is difficult for it to get out of there, this causes the softening of all layers of the coating and, consequently, the formation of pits.
During the formation of pits, he said, the first wear layer and only then it affects the bitumen, but the damage does not occur instantly, it is a process that should be paid attention at the first signs of routine maintenance programs.
Also, a member of the National System of Researchers explained that the transport load is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each layer of coating should always be associated with the transport load and it is necessary to guarantee compliance with this requirement to prevent the frequent occurrence of holes.
Rafael Herrera said that there is still a lot to learn and do about bitumen, for example, bitumen emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries and even help repair pits with ease and without using high temperatures.
