Introduction of the “golden rule” of the budget into the constitution
The leadership of the large coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to write a budget “golden rule” in the constitution to reduce the budget deficit and thus avoid a possible downgrade by rating agencies of the state credit rating of Austria (triple A).
Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann personally announced the decision at the end of the Council of Ministers meeting, with Austrian public debt at 74.6%, well above the upper 60% threshold set by the Maastricht Treaty but below the public debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
If Austria’s solvency had fallen by only one point, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay interest of three thousand million euros more each year, Vice Chancellor and Christian Democrat Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger argued.
Thus, Austria fulfills the demand of the summit of the member countries of the Eurozone on October 26 in Brussels; the heads of state and government demanded the reduction of budget deficits by the end of 2012 and the return to balanced public accounts through a constitution or equivalent law.
The ruling adopted by the Austrian government resembles the "German model", as Germany was the first European country to adopt this "rule".
Until 2017, the structural deficit of the state budget should be reduced every year by 0.75% of the gross domestic product (GDP), and since 2017 the structural deficit of the state budget of the federal state in any year should not exceed 0.35% of GDP, and the land, like the communes, should represent balanced budgets.
The goal is to force the national debt to fall below the 60% mark fixed by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/2021.
